SIMPLE: speculation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Speculation
<hw>Spec`u*la"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>speculatio</ets> a spying out, observation: cf. F.
<ets>sp⟦eacute⟧culation</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of
speculating.</def> Specifically: --⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(a)</sd> <def>Examination by the eye; view.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>Mental view of anything in its various aspects and
relations; contemplation; intellectual examination.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thenceforth to <qex>speculations</qex> high or deep⟦br⟧
I turned my thoughts.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <fld>(Philos.)</fld> <def>The act or process of
reasoning <it>a priori</it> from premises given or assumed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(d)</sd> <fld>(Com.)</fld> <def>The act or practice of buying
land, goods, shares, etc., in expectation of selling at a higher price,
or of selling with the expectation of repurchasing at a lower price; a
trading on anticipated fluctuations in price, as distinguished from
trading in which the profit expected is the difference between the
retail and wholesale prices, or the difference of price in different
markets.</def> <-- buying long is considered speculation only when the
time of holding the object is short. Longer-term trading (⟦gt⟧ 1 year)
is considered investment. -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sudden fortunes, indeed, are sometimes made in such places, by
what is called the trade of <qex>speculation</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>A.
Smith.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Speculation</qex>, while confined within moderate limits, is
the agent for equalizing supply and demand, and rendering the
fluctuations of price less sudden and abrupt than they would otherwise
be.</q> <rj><qau>F. A. Walker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(e)</sd> <def>Any business venture in involving unusual risks,
with a chance for large profits.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A conclusion to which the mind comes by speculating;
mere theory; view; notion; conjecture.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>From him Socrates derived the principles of morality, and most
part of his natural <qex>speculations</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Temple.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To his <qex>speculations</qex> on these subjects he gave the lofty
name of the ⟦ldquo⟧Oracles of Reason.⟦rdquo⟧</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Power of sight.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou hast no <qex>speculation</qex> in those eyes.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A game at cards in which the players buy from one
another trumps or whole hands, upon a chance of getting the highest
trump dealt, which entitles the holder to the pool of stakes.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Speculatist</ent>⟦br⟧
